288
00:16:02,632 --> 00:16:05,001
Scott: Yeah, just if you don't like it, don't look at it.

289
00:16:05,282 --> 00:16:05,563
Rym: Yeah.

290
00:16:05,984 --> 00:16:10,240
Scott: I mean, granted, if you want, you can be like China and filter it all out.

291
00:16:10,581 --> 00:16:12,107
Rym: Yeah, we know how well that's working.

292
00:16:12,388 --> 00:16:15,054
Scott: Yeah, I mean, I'm not really too upset.

293
00:16:15,074 --> 00:16:16,639
Scott: I mean, sure, it's wrong.

294
00:16:17,120 --> 00:16:23,460
Scott: If I had my way, China would have, you know, but that's what China has done.

295
00:16:23,541 --> 00:16:26,110
Scott: And they're allowed to do that within their own country.

296
00:16:26,811 --> 00:16:29,480
Scott: And, you know, it doesn't really hurt me.

297
00:16:30,002 --> 00:16:39,635
Rym: So, yeah, of course, also, it just comes down to the very simple fact that if you were ever offended by something on the Internet, good, you don't belong on the Internet anymore.

298
00:16:39,696 --> 00:16:41,542
Scott: Welcome to the new world.

299
00:16:42,105 --> 00:16:43,048
Scott: Congratulations.

300
00:16:43,088 --> 00:16:46,841
Scott: The first two digits of the year are now two zero and not one nine.

301
00:16:46,962 --> 00:16:47,785
Rym: Luckily, wake up.

302
00:16:48,226 --> 00:16:50,698
Rym: It's pretty easy to avoid things that offend you on the Internet.

303
00:16:51,080 --> 00:16:55,442
Rym: I mean, if you're a person who can be offended, just don't go to any of the good sites and you won't see any of those things.

304
00:16:55,663 --> 00:16:56,729
Scott: Just don't go anywhere.

305
00:16:56,769 --> 00:16:57,452
Scott: Don't go to Fark.

306
00:16:57,572 --> 00:16:58,978
Scott: You just stick with Google News.

307
00:16:59,079 --> 00:17:02,574
Scott: You'll probably never be offended except by actual real world happenings.

308
00:17:02,694 --> 00:17:10,450
Rym: It always amazes me when I'll be on Fark and there'll be a headline and someone makes light of the fact that someone died due to their own stupidity in some sort of hilarious way.

309
00:17:11,391 --> 00:17:18,517
Rym: And then there's always that one guy who posts about how offended he is that someone had the audacity to make fun of something on the Internet.

310
00:17:19,861 --> 00:17:22,789
Scott: But that guy, I want to meet that guy.

311
00:17:23,931 --> 00:17:28,085
Rym: For all we know, it's just one guy and he just has an account.

312
00:17:28,145 --> 00:17:28,847
Scott: It's a spark.

313
00:17:28,907 --> 00:17:30,272
Scott: It's probably just a guy pretending.

314
00:17:30,754 --> 00:17:32,198
Rym: See, it's hard to tell anymore.

315
00:17:32,540 --> 00:17:35,530
Rym: Fark is so full of trolls, but not bad trolls.

316
00:17:35,550 --> 00:17:41,371
Rym: I mean, there are bad trolls, but also good trolls that I usually cannot tell if someone is trolling or just stupid.

317
00:17:41,652 --> 00:17:58,452
Scott: This is why when I read posts on the Internet, like text that someone has posted on the Internet, I take the collective body of work someone has written in their forum posts and emails and blog posts and whatever, and I consider that to be like a separate entity from the person themselves.

318
00:17:58,834 --> 00:18:03,775
Scott: What someone posts on the Internet tells me nothing about the actual person whatsoever and I assume nothing.

319
00:18:04,076 --> 00:18:06,567
Scott: The problem is a lot of other people do not follow this rule.

320
00:18:06,808 --> 00:18:15,243
Scott: So they'll read something I've written and assume a lot of things about me based on their interpretation of what I've done or written in some forum somewhere.

321
00:18:15,343 --> 00:18:16,588
