Scott: So it doesn't look so great when you're up close, you got to sit far back from it.

458
00:25:56,810 --> 00:25:57,955
Scott: And then what's, what's the point?

459
00:25:58,477 --> 00:26:04,260
Scott: if the pixels on that monitor was there as small as the ones on my LCD on my laptop, that'd be the best monitor in the world.

460
00:26:04,581 --> 00:26:15,373
Rym: But anyway, one of the most important parts of a computer, if you're going to build one, and I guess it matters if you're getting one from Dell or gateway or whatever, because a lot of them, especially like those Alienwares offer special ones.

461
00:26:15,935 --> 00:26:20,070
Rym: The computer case is actually something you got to put some thought into.

462
00:26:20,451 --> 00:26:21,736
Scott: Also known as the chassis.

463
00:26:22,078 --> 00:26:31,238
Scott: It's basically for those of you who don't know, you have a computer, it's a motherboard and a video card and a bunch of chips and wires and things like that, but you got to put those things in a box.

464
00:26:31,319 --> 00:26:32,082
Rym: You don't have to.

465
00:26:32,102 --> 00:26:39,918
Rym: I have more than once run a computer that was literally a motherboard sitting on a piece of cardboard and a bunch of hard drives and stuff plugged into it, just laying next to it.

466
00:26:40,320 --> 00:26:44,960
Scott: However, this can be problematic because number one, your computer is not protected from the elements.

467
00:26:45,583 --> 00:26:47,913
Scott: So you don't want to have a computer lying open.

468
00:26:47,953 --> 00:26:50,024
Scott: If you spill a coffee or something, you're screwed.

469
00:26:50,204 --> 00:26:51,952
Rym: Oh, if your friend Scott Johnson comes over.

470
00:26:52,434 --> 00:26:52,675
Scott: Yup.

471
00:26:52,896 --> 00:26:56,248
Scott: Number two, the computer is not protected from static discharge.

472
00:26:56,368 --> 00:26:58,418
Rym: If say, if your friend Scott Johnson comes over.

473
00:26:58,478 --> 00:26:58,759
Rym: Yes.

474
00:26:58,940 --> 00:27:08,076
Scott: If your friend Scott Johnson comes over, he might statically shock your motherboard from a few feet away after rubbing his wool socks on your carpet and then game over computer.

475
00:27:08,096 --> 00:27:13,110
Scott: The case of the computer serves a few important functions.

476
00:27:13,331 --> 00:27:16,646
Scott: Number one, it protects the case from the elements as I just said.

477
00:27:16,666 --> 00:27:18,775
Rym: Well, it protects the computer from the elements.

478
00:27:18,815 --> 00:27:26,165
Rym: The case does not protect itself unless you have some sort of meta case, perhaps a case case, some sort of encasement around the case.

479
00:27:26,266 --> 00:27:26,587
Rym: Yes.

480
00:27:26,727 --> 00:27:27,028
Scott: Okay.

481
00:27:27,069 --> 00:27:28,657
Scott: Protects the computer from the element.

482
00:27:28,718 --> 00:27:33,023
Rym: It's like those people who have a nice couch and then they put a plastic sheet over it because they're afraid of it getting ruined.

483
00:27:33,064 --> 00:27:35,074
Rym: Thus defeating the purpose of having the nice couch.

484
00:27:35,254 --> 00:27:35,495
Rym: Yes.

485
00:27:35,997 --> 00:27:40,417
Scott: But yeah, if you don't have a, if you have a case, you don't have to worry about spilling something.

486
00:27:40,477 --> 00:27:41,000
Scott: I mean, sure.

487
00:27:41,121 --> 00:27:43,132
Scott: You might spill something on it, but it's not the end world.

488
00:27:43,172 --> 00:27:46,730
Rym: Dude, if you spill something on your computer case, what the hell were you doing?

489
00:27:47,431 --> 00:27:47,531
Scott: Yeah.

490
00:27:47,552 --> 00:27:52,314
Scott: You can also, you know, it takes all the components and it makes them take up a lot less physical space.

491
00:27:52,334 --> 00:27:55,652
Scott: You know, a motherboard with a bunch of hard drives strewn about takes up your whole desk.

492
00:27:55,993 --> 00:28:02,062
Scott: If you cram those things into a nice box, you can get them in there real tight, you know, and then it takes up a lot less space in your room.

493
00:28:02,102 --> 00:28:04,433
Scott: You can stick the computer in the closet or under your desk.

494
00:28:04,614 --> 00:28:06,320
Rym: Especially with towers.

495
00:28:06,340 --> 00:28:06,481
Rym: Cause.

496
00:28:06,501 --> 00:28:10,415
Rym: remember back in the day, most computers were not towers like we see today.

497
00:28:10,495 --> 00:28:15,958
Rym: Most of them were big, wide chunks of things that sat on your desk and you stuck the monitor on top of them.

498
00:28:16,279 --> 00:28:19,556
Rym: And they took up a bunch of space and they didn't take advantage of that vertical space.

499
00:28:19,818 --> 00:28:19,978
Scott: Yeah.

500
00:28:19,998 --> 00:28:23,493
Scott: A lot of computers used to have the, like the keyboard, like an Apple too.

501
00:28:23,634 --> 00:28:30,339
Scott: The keyboard and the computer are part of the same physical thing or a Macintosh old school, like a 512 K or a Mac plus.

502
00:28:30,720 --> 00:28:34,672
Scott: the monitor and the computer and the disc drive are all part of the same.

503
00:28:34,692 --> 00:28:36,178
Scott: They're all one thing like an iMac.

504
00:28:36,218 --> 00:28:37,241
Scott: It's one thing.

505
00:28:37,261 --> 00:28:44,030
Scott: And that took up a lot of room back in the day when monitors were big and keyboards were big and it, it kind of sucked.

506
00:28:44,530 --> 00:28:55,108
Scott: Well, now that we have the tower, you can cram the tower somewhere far away, use extra long cables or even wireless and just have on your desk, a monitor, a nice LCD monitor.

507
00:28:55,128 --> 00:29:00,390
Scott: It doesn't take up much room, a keyboard and a mouse and have all the other stuff far away where it doesn't bother you.

508
00:29:00,791 --> 00:29:08,664
Rym: Now, the funny thing is in terms of what kinds of computers geeks build, there was almost an arms race in terms of how big towers could be.

509
00:29:08,965 --> 00:29:14,792
Rym: And the conventional wisdom back in the day was get the biggest goddamn tower you can afford because you're going to fill it with drives.

510
00:29:14,892 --> 00:29:21,252
Rym: And nowadays all those drives have basically been condensed into one drive or two drives.

511
00:29:21,292 --> 00:29:29,324
Scott: But yet again, more and more motherboards are coming with Raid and more and more people are doing simple raids in their homes to store their vast media collections.

512
00:29:29,846 --> 00:29:31,595
Scott: And we're going back to having lots of drives.

513
00:29:31,716 --> 00:29:31,917
Rym: Yep.

514
00:29:31,977 --> 00:29:38,625
Rym: But at the same time, while you're getting all these drives on the inside now, you don't need nearly as many outward facing drives as you used to.

515
00:29:38,705 --> 00:29:43,421
Rym: I mean, the case I use for my current computer, my old one, is gigantic.

516
00:29:43,782 --> 00:29:44,966
Rym: It's absolutely huge.

517
00:29:45,488 --> 00:29:51,768
Rym: It has a whole bunch of open spaces in the front, the five inch bays, and four of them are full of stuff.

518
00:29:51,869 --> 00:29:53,073
Rym: I got my CD burner.

519
00:29:53,354 --> 00:29:54,578
Rym: I got my DVD ROM.

520
00:29:54,819 --> 00:29:57,549
Rym: I got my zip drive that hasn't worked in God knows how long.

521
00:29:57,589 --> 00:29:57,730
Rym: Yep.

522
00:29:57,950 --> 00:29:59,094
Rym: I got my live drive.

523
00:29:59,355 --> 00:30:02,908
Rym: Maybe if I want some sort of card reader that takes up another one.

524
00:30:02,928 --> 00:30:05,136
Rym: But nowadays you don't need all that stuff.

525
00:30:05,457 --> 00:30:06,903
Rym: No one uses zip drives anymore.

526
00:30:06,923 --> 00:30:07,425
Rym: Nope.

527
00:30:07,887 --> 00:30:08,128
Scott: Yeah.

528
00:30:08,228 --> 00:30:11,342
Scott: Back in the late 90s, like the full tower was where it's at.

529
00:30:11,382 --> 00:30:15,478
Scott: You kind of needed a full tower, mostly because also a lot of motherboards are really big.

530
00:30:15,599 --> 00:30:22,141
Scott: And the design of cases hadn't progressed much because, the standards for how these things worked were new.

531
00:30:22,161 --> 00:30:25,955
Scott: Up until then, people just made the entire computer as a unit.

532
00:30:25,995 --> 00:30:29,752
Scott: The case was designed for the motherboard and all these parts were designed to go together.

533
00:30:30,294 --> 00:30:36,576
Scott: And you wouldn't just have a motherboard designed in such a way that any case could have that motherboard.

534
00:30:36,596 --> 00:30:42,479
Scott: Or any motherboard could take any case and any case could take any motherboard and any drive could fit in any box.

535
00:30:42,941 --> 00:30:47,581
Scott: But we came up with standards for those things and everyone followed the same rules and now it's awesome.

536
00:30:47,842 --> 00:30:48,043
Rym: Yep.

537
00:30:48,385 --> 00:30:52,881
Rym: I mean, you might hear things like, oh, it's an ATX or it's a micro ATX or it's a BTX.

538
00:30:53,443 --> 00:30:58,300
Rym: Those are the standards that cases use in order to determine what kinds of motherboards can go in them.

539
00:30:58,360 --> 00:30:58,561
Rym: Yep.

540
00:30:58,661 --> 00:31:05,770
Scott: So if a case says I can take an ATX motherboard, well, any ATX motherboard will now fit in that case, guaranteed pretty much.

541
00:31:06,270 --> 00:31:18,522
Scott: That tells you how big the motherboard is, where the holes are to put the screws in, what kind of connector for the power supply you'll have, all sorts of stuff like that is determined by the ATX standard.

542
00:31:18,762 --> 00:31:20,610
Rym: Now, the original standard was AT.

543
00:31:20,890 --> 00:31:22,798
Rym: It stands for Advanced Technology.

544
00:31:22,878 --> 00:31:23,099
Scott: Yep.

545
00:31:23,139 --> 00:31:25,509
Scott: That was the standard set by the IBM AT.

546
00:31:26,551 --> 00:31:29,301
Scott: Oh, there was a computer called the IBM AT.

547
00:31:29,602 --> 00:31:41,142
Scott: That's why we always talk about the places where we used to plug in mice and keyboards on computers before we invented USB are called PS2 ports, because those are the same ports that we had in the IBM PS2.

548
00:31:41,162 --> 00:31:41,603
Rym: Yeah.

549
00:31:41,643 --> 00:31:44,371
Rym: Before that, we actually got a jackpot.

550
00:31:44,752 --> 00:31:48,820
Rym: Well, I guess jackpot is a relative term of like 20 or 30 AT style or XD.

551
00:31:48,840 --> 00:31:48,921
Rym: Yeah.

552
00:31:48,941 --> 00:31:54,213
Rym: I think those were ATs.

553
00:31:54,374 --> 00:31:54,655
Scott: Yeah.

554
00:31:54,695 --> 00:32:00,278
Scott: But you know, yeah, they used to call it the IBM AT or XT connector was, it looked like a big PS2 port.

555
00:32:00,359 --> 00:32:04,219
Scott: And that's what they used to use to connect the keyboards and the mice to the most of the keyboards.

556
00:32:04,280 --> 00:32:04,381
Rym: Yeah.

557
00:32:04,401 --> 00:32:05,367
Rym: We got all those keyboards.

558
00:32:05,387 --> 00:32:06,754
Rym: We thought, oh, sell them on eBay.

559
00:32:06,995 --> 00:32:08,583
Rym: And then a year went by and we threw them all away.

560
00:32:08,844 --> 00:32:09,025
Scott: Yep.

561
00:32:09,487 --> 00:32:11,013
Rym: Like all those bikes we got by that.

562
00:32:11,536 --> 00:32:15,171
Rym: That's a whole other story from the one time we thought dumpster diving was a good idea.

563
00:32:15,332 --> 00:32:15,532
Rym: Yep.

564
00:32:15,954 --> 00:32:24,964
Scott: But yeah, ATX has been and continues to be the primary standard for these things since pretty much the mid nineties when ATX took over as the standard.

565
00:32:25,165 --> 00:32:25,345
Rym: Yep.

566
00:32:25,807 --> 00:32:26,429
Scott: I mean, sure.

567
00:32:26,449 --> 00:32:27,493
Scott: There are some other standards.

568
00:32:27,534 --> 00:32:28,980
Scott: There's some BTXs out there.

569
00:32:29,080 --> 00:32:31,490
Rym: BTX is really only for like pre-built computers.

570
00:32:31,770 --> 00:32:31,931
Rym: Yeah.

571
00:32:32,152 --> 00:32:32,957
Rym: Don't worry about it.

572
00:32:33,037 --> 00:32:34,968
Rym: If you get a BTX computer, you didn't build it.

573
00:32:35,008 --> 00:32:35,691
Rym: So it doesn't matter.

574
00:32:35,731 --> 00:32:35,932
Scott: Yep.

575
00:32:36,535 --> 00:32:41,253
Scott: The thing is BTX and other new standards actually offer a lot of things that ATX can't do.

576
00:32:41,815 --> 00:32:49,179
Scott: Mostly things like we position the CPU on the motherboard for better cooling than ATX can offer and things like that.

577
00:32:49,741 --> 00:32:55,684
Scott: And it's actually better, but because the ATX standard is so ingrained and it's good enough, people tend to stick with it.

578
00:32:55,865 --> 00:33:03,435
Scott: And if they suddenly just stop making ATX stuff, a lot of people would be out in the lurch a lot more than when they change CPU sockets or anything like that.

579
00:33:03,535 --> 00:33:10,301
Rym: So really all you need to worry about now are ATX and micro ATX and everything else you'll really not run into.

580
00:33:10,341 --> 00:33:13,718
Scott: Now there's mini ATX, but I don't know if that's different from micro or if they're the same.

581
00:33:13,758 --> 00:33:14,482
Scott: It doesn't really matter.

582
00:33:14,502 --> 00:33:16,833
Rym: I am reasonably certain that it's different.

583
00:33:17,094 --> 00:33:17,435
Scott: Yeah.

584
00:33:17,455 --> 00:33:17,656
Scott: Okay.

585
00:33:18,057 --> 00:33:18,318
Scott: Anyway.

586
00:33:18,620 --> 00:33:18,780
Rym: Yeah.

587
00:33:18,861 --> 00:33:23,117
Rym: And very briefly, the only real difference is that micro ATX is obviously smaller.

588
00:33:23,619 --> 00:33:30,770
Rym: And if you're building a gaming computer, you probably want an ATX motherboard because they use that extra space to put a lot of extra stuff on the motherboard.

589
00:33:31,252 --> 00:33:36,597
Rym: But if you're just making a computer for your grandma or a normal computer, just for, you know, email or a living room computer.

590
00:33:36,617 --> 00:33:37,100
Scott: Yeah.

591
00:33:37,140 --> 00:33:43,467
Rym: Anything that has to be small, anything that doesn't have to be super, super high performing micro ATX motherboards are pretty bad ass.

592
00:33:43,849 --> 00:33:44,029
Scott: Yeah.

593
00:33:44,069 --> 00:33:45,596
Scott: You can get a really good motherboard.

594
00:33:45,857 --> 00:33:48,530
Scott: It just will probably have like fewer connectors on it.

595
00:33:48,570 --> 00:33:52,126
Scott: So you might not get SLI and you probably, oh, you're not going to get SLI.

596
00:33:52,146 --> 00:33:53,812
Scott: I think there might actually be a few with SLI.

597
00:33:54,073 --> 00:34:09,591
Scott: You might not get a really good cooling because it's kind of small and it's a lot of connectors for a whole bunch of hard drives because a tiny case doesn't have room for a whole bunch of hard drives anyway, but you'll get a really small computer that does the job.

598
00:34:09,933 --> 00:34:15,815
Scott: So, you know, when you're building a computer, that's probably the first thing you have to decide is, is it going to be an ATX?

599
00:34:15,835 --> 00:34:17,422
Scott: Cause I need a full add on computer.

600
00:34:17,924 --> 00:34:19,330
Scott: Or can I go with the micro ATX?

601
00:34:19,409 --> 00:34:21,280
Scott: Cause I'd rather have something smaller and quieter.

602
00:34:21,681 --> 00:34:26,199
Rym: Now the other very important factor in a case is that one function it provides is cooling.

603
00:34:27,023 --> 00:34:28,327
Rym: It'll draw air in the front.

604
00:34:28,688 --> 00:34:29,893
Rym: It'll pull air out the back.

605
00:34:30,174 --> 00:34:33,387
Rym: Fans are usually arranged in a certain way to maximize cooling.

606
00:34:33,688 --> 00:34:35,295
Rym: Sometimes you have the blow hole in the side.

607
00:34:35,556 --> 00:34:36,904
Rym: There's extra exhaust in the top.

608
00:34:37,186 --> 00:34:41,041
Rym: You got to decide if you want a positive pressure or a negative pressure system, all those fun things.

609
00:34:41,262 --> 00:34:41,422
Scott: Yep.

610
00:34:41,925 --> 00:34:54,011
Scott: Basically you want a computer that takes in lots of cold air from the outside of the computer and pushes lots of hot air that the computer that they can, well, air that the computer has made hot outside of the computer.

611
00:34:54,453 --> 00:35:06,399
Scott: Usually you want exhaust fans in the top and in the back where the hot air is likely to be and intake fans in the front and the bottom where there's not so much hot air in the computer and you're going to pull in air from the outside.

612
00:35:06,660 --> 00:35:16,746
Rym: See in the early days, pretty much every case was the same and there was always the one front air intake and then the one back exhaust and then the power supply, which you stick in there acted as kind of an auxiliary exhaust.

613
00:35:16,807 --> 00:35:21,067
Scott: Well, the power supply has its own exhaust because the power supply itself makes a lot of heat.

614
00:35:21,308 --> 00:35:29,239
Rym: Yeah, but it also drew air out of the rest of the computer, which was usually already hot, which probably contributed to a lot of those early power supply failures.

615
00:35:29,520 --> 00:35:30,223
Scott: Probably.

616
00:35:30,243 --> 00:35:32,671
Scott: Yeah, but generally one rule is.

617
00:35:32,912 --> 00:35:36,284
Scott: you might think, oh, I want a lot more exhaust than I want intake.

618
00:35:36,666 --> 00:35:47,329
Rym: And in fact, a lot of earlier cases required that to work well because they'd usually have along the sides in the front a giant vent that you couldn't put a fan on, but they expected the air to be pulled in from there.

619
00:35:47,369 --> 00:35:50,846
Rym: So you needed a lot of exhaust to pull air through and cool the whole case.

620
00:35:50,906 --> 00:35:56,211
Scott: Yep, because if you have a lot of exhaust, the air pressure outside the case is greater than the air pressure inside the case.

621
00:35:56,291 --> 00:36:00,787
Scott: And thus air will just push its way into your case on its own without any fan help.

622
00:36:01,349 --> 00:36:06,852
Scott: The problem with that is, of course, that dust goes right into the case because the dust will go in with the air.

623
00:36:06,973 --> 00:36:11,532
Rym: Well, more importantly, dust gets into the case from every single hole that the case has.

624
00:36:11,552 --> 00:36:12,114
Rym: Yep.

625
00:36:12,515 --> 00:36:18,235
Scott: This is why the new modern thinking is to have a positive pressure case where there is more intake than exhaust.

626
00:36:18,295 --> 00:36:23,836
Scott: The intake fans will pull in lots of air through a filter of some sort, which will collect all the dust.

627
00:36:24,319 --> 00:36:28,196
Scott: And the air pressure inside your case will be greater than the air pressure outside your case.

628
00:36:28,256 --> 00:36:30,867
Scott: And thus, dust really won't get in there so much.

629
00:36:31,209 --> 00:36:36,723
Scott: But you still will have enough exhaust to push the hot air in your case out.

630
00:36:37,345 --> 00:36:39,772
Scott: And yeah, your computer will stay cool.

631
00:36:40,274 --> 00:36:42,704
Rym: Now it depends very much on what kind of case you have.

632
00:36:43,065 --> 00:36:46,922
Rym: So don't automatically go positive pressure, at least look at your case, figure it out.

633
00:36:47,304 --> 00:36:48,691
Rym: You don't want to just fiddle with it.

634
00:36:48,711 --> 00:36:52,487
Rym: Case is usually designed fairly specifically to be cooled in a certain way.

635
00:36:52,748 --> 00:36:59,439
Rym: And if you start putting fans in places where you weren't supposed to put fans and they're facing the wrong direction, you're probably going to have some cooling trouble.

636
00:36:59,640 --> 00:36:59,861
Scott: Yep.

637
00:37:00,223 --> 00:37:08,075
Scott: So just your case will either come with fans or it will have spots where fans obviously go and it'll be obvious which direction those fans should be blowing.

638
00:37:08,436 --> 00:37:09,963
Scott: Just do whatever the case wants.

639
00:37:10,365 --> 00:37:11,329
Scott: The case knows best.

640
00:37:11,369 --> 00:37:12,975
Scott: The people designing the case figured it out.

641
00:37:13,377 --> 00:37:17,312
Rym: Now the third and more recent use for a case is to show off your bling.

642
00:37:17,633 --> 00:37:18,596
Scott: Bling a blingy.

643
00:37:18,757 --> 00:37:27,985
Rym: You should see, I mean, a lot of cases now have windows in the side or cold cathode tubes or they make noise or the fans have colors in them.

644
00:37:28,046 --> 00:37:31,477
Rym: And this is a relatively in the last several years, new development.

645
00:37:31,859 --> 00:37:33,786
Rym: Cases used to all be the same color.

646
00:37:34,148 --> 00:37:36,295
Scott: Everyone used to get like the just the light.

647
00:37:36,516 --> 00:37:45,528
Scott: eight, seven, whatever it was called case, which is a plain beige box that was really good at holding your motherboard and really good at holding drives.

648
00:37:45,568 --> 00:37:47,718
Scott: And that it did its function correctly.

649
00:37:47,939 --> 00:37:50,371
Scott: And that was the case that people bought because it was cheap and it worked.

650
00:37:50,813 --> 00:37:53,524
Scott: And no one really cared if your case was some other color.

651
00:37:53,544 --> 00:37:58,600
Scott: But then I don't know who did it, but they made a black computer and people were like, ooh.

652
00:37:59,142 --> 00:38:02,414
Scott: And then someone decided to mod their case.

653
00:38:02,454 --> 00:38:03,279
Scott: They said, hey, you know what?

654
00:38:03,460 --> 00:38:04,990
Scott: I want to look at my computer while I'm using it.

655
00:38:05,010 --> 00:38:10,194
Scott: And they cut a hole in the side of their box and they put a piece of plexiglass over it and they could see into their computer.

656
00:38:10,536 --> 00:38:12,363
Scott: I wish I could find that original case mod.

657
00:38:12,765 --> 00:38:15,033
Scott: I remember seeing it on like gadget or something.

658
00:38:15,214 --> 00:38:18,646
Rym: And it started this gigantic wave of people modding cases.

659
00:38:18,687 --> 00:38:18,907
Scott: Yep.

660
00:38:19,188 --> 00:38:21,156
Scott: People started modding cases left and right.

661
00:38:21,397 --> 00:38:23,425
Rym: So some genius entrepreneurs said, you know what?

662
00:38:24,007 --> 00:38:33,120
Rym: Much like the Honda Civic, we should start marketing certain kinds of cases to the people who want all that and make it easy for them to show off their bling.

663
00:38:33,401 --> 00:38:35,790
Rym: So they started coming with all these tubes in them.

664
00:38:35,850 --> 00:38:39,442
Rym: In fact, Scott's current case has blue lights on the inside.

665
00:38:39,603 --> 00:38:43,517
Scott: Yeah, it has a blue light and it has a clear window in the side.

666
00:38:43,898 --> 00:38:46,168
Scott: My next case probably will not have those things.

667
00:38:46,389 --> 00:38:46,690
Rym: Good.

668
00:38:48,291 --> 00:38:49,416
Scott: Yeah, I don't know what I was thinking.

669
00:38:49,697 --> 00:38:55,158
Rym: Yeah, well, the case I'm getting now is the Antec P180 silver cold rolled steel thing.

670
00:38:55,198 --> 00:38:57,585
Rym: weighs a fuck ton, but it's plain.

671
00:38:57,665 --> 00:38:58,187
Rym: It's steel.

672
00:38:58,468 --> 00:39:02,882
Rym: It looks sturdy and it's got the power supply in the bottom instead of on top.

673
00:39:03,223 --> 00:39:04,146
Rym: It's kind of weird.

674
00:39:04,166 --> 00:39:05,451
Rym: A lot of people like that.

675
00:39:05,492 --> 00:39:08,410
Rym: I'm not sure if it's going to be good, but I'm going to roll with the only problem with it.

676
00:39:08,490 --> 00:39:10,215
Scott: It's obviously a better position.

677
00:39:10,777 --> 00:39:17,621
Scott: The only problem I can see is if the wires from the power supply can reach the rest of the computer from the bottom.

678
00:39:17,761 --> 00:39:17,942
Rym: Yep.

679
00:39:18,083 --> 00:39:21,717
Rym: Luckily, I bought an Antec power supply that I'm pretty sure will reach.

680
00:39:22,721 --> 00:39:25,994
Rym: And I see more people saying good things about the case than bad things.

681
00:39:26,335 --> 00:39:28,705
Scott: So it definitely looks like a quality case.

682
00:39:29,026 --> 00:39:29,227
Rym: Yeah.

683
00:39:29,448 --> 00:39:35,856
Rym: And the thing is, it's not super blingy because I really don't want to waste my precious wattages with lights and fancy bullshit.

684
00:39:35,996 --> 00:39:43,152
Scott: Yeah, well, the window on the case actually has a useful function that if there's something going on in the computer, I don't have to open it up to find out what the deal is.

685
00:39:43,232 --> 00:39:46,812
Rym: I remember when I think your Northbridge fan stopped spinning and you never would have known that.

686
00:39:47,294 --> 00:39:47,515
Scott: Yep.

687
00:39:47,816 --> 00:39:50,547
Scott: But then I looked and, oh, look, my fan stopped spinning.

688
00:39:50,587 --> 00:39:51,169
Scott: That's no good.

689
00:39:52,912 --> 00:39:53,755
Scott: The window's useful.

690
00:39:53,775 --> 00:39:55,021
Scott: The light, not so useful.

691
00:39:55,061 --> 00:40:01,043
Rym: Well, even though most modern motherboards, you can find out rather easily if a fan stops spinning in software.

692
00:40:01,224 --> 00:40:01,967
Scott: Yeah.

693
00:40:02,047 --> 00:40:04,498
Scott: But you have to have something set up to do that.

694
00:40:04,518 --> 00:40:07,432
Scott: And, you know, it's not as easy as just looking with your eyeball.

695
00:40:07,672 --> 00:40:08,475
Scott: Yeah.

696
00:40:09,037 --> 00:40:09,258
Scott: Yeah.

697
00:40:09,338 --> 00:40:11,746
Scott: Another important thing to note about cases is the material.

698
00:40:12,247 --> 00:40:15,257
Scott: All cases used to just be made out of steel and plastic.

699
00:40:15,779 --> 00:40:21,015
Scott: And that was okay for a time, but computers are heavy and really sucked.

700
00:40:21,677 --> 00:40:23,985
Scott: And it generally just sucked all around.

701
00:40:24,045 --> 00:40:30,405
Rym: I remember going to my first LAN party and three of us crammed into my tiny little laser to drive to Southfield.

702
00:40:30,726 --> 00:40:36,906
Rym: So everyone except the driver sat with a monitor, a CRT, a gigantic CRT in their lap.

703
00:40:37,287 --> 00:40:40,399
Rym: And the computers, which were gigantic, barely fit in the trunk.

704
00:40:40,780 --> 00:40:42,728
Rym: And my, my suspension could barely take it.

705
00:40:42,748 --> 00:40:43,652
Rym: And it totally sucked.

706
00:40:43,772 --> 00:40:43,993
Scott: Yep.

707
00:40:44,475 --> 00:40:48,630
Scott: Now they decided they would make cases out of, you know, couldn't do just plastic.

708
00:40:48,770 --> 00:40:52,386
Scott: The problem with just plastic is you can't ground your motherboard on plastic.

709
00:40:52,768 --> 00:40:56,262
Scott: It needs to be grounded so that the aforementioned static shocks do not happen.

710
00:40:56,684 --> 00:41:01,263
Scott: Your case must form some sort of cage to protect your computer from the electrical elements.

711
00:41:01,484 --> 00:41:03,392
Rym: Even though mine currently definitely does not.

712
00:41:03,452 --> 00:41:06,444
Scott: Yes, but a total plastic case does not work.

713
00:41:06,524 --> 00:41:10,518
Scott: So they need some sort of metal and thus the aluminum case or the aluminum.

714
00:41:10,598 --> 00:41:10,779
Rym: Yep.

715
00:41:11,220 --> 00:41:17,963
Scott: They make lots of aluminum cases now or aluminum alloys or various other metals, which are just as protective from the elements.

716
00:41:18,385 --> 00:41:20,393
Scott: They look better sometimes and they're much lighter.

717
00:41:20,413 --> 00:41:22,764
Scott: So you can pick your computer up and move it around.

718
00:41:22,985 --> 00:41:23,186
Rym: Yep.

719
00:41:23,588 --> 00:41:26,482
Rym: And also a lot of cases are LAN party ready now where they'll.

720
00:41:26,563 --> 00:41:31,505
Rym: not only will they be small and compact and ready to go and look really cool, but they usually have carrying cases.

721
00:41:31,565 --> 00:41:36,301
Rym: You can buy special or handles backpack things to carry them around with you.

722
00:41:36,482 --> 00:41:36,662
Rym: Yep.

723
00:41:37,966 --> 00:41:38,227
Scott: All right.

724
00:41:38,267 --> 00:41:43,749
Scott: So Rym, when you're looking for a case, how do you decide which case is good and which case is not so good?

725
00:41:43,929 --> 00:41:50,459
Rym: Well, when I was young and inexperienced, I would get the biggest case I could afford that had the most possible places to put things.

726
00:41:50,901 --> 00:42:00,132
Rym: My current case has spots for two power supplies because I always thought that someday I'll fill this case with drives and I'll get another power supply just for them.

727
00:42:01,936 --> 00:42:02,296
Rym: Yeah.

728
00:42:02,557 --> 00:42:02,817
Rym: Yeah.

729
00:42:02,857 --> 00:42:04,781
Scott: Technology will only ever need 460 K. Yeah.

730
00:42:04,801 --> 00:42:11,621
Rym: Nowadays really to me, I want a case that's small.

731
00:42:11,641 --> 00:42:12,345
Rym: I want a mid tower.

732
00:42:12,365 --> 00:42:15,017
Rym: I don't want some gigantic tower with a million things.

733
00:42:15,158 --> 00:42:17,147
Scott: I've only ever bought mid towers, but yeah.

734
00:42:17,509 --> 00:42:17,630
Rym: Yeah.

735
00:42:17,650 --> 00:42:24,938
Scott: Well, I've only ever bought full towers and actually like something smaller than a mid tower, but they just won't fit everything I want in there.

736
00:42:25,379 --> 00:42:29,152
Rym: What I really want is ease of access and ease of installation.

737
00:42:29,675 --> 00:42:34,234
Rym: I want a case where I can pull the hard drive cage out, fill it up with hard drives and put it back in.

738
00:42:34,394 --> 00:42:34,555
Rym: Yeah.

739
00:42:34,635 --> 00:42:40,098
Rym: I want a case where all the fans and all the hard drives are mounted on rails with fricking rubber grommets.

740
00:42:40,399 --> 00:42:41,343
Rym: So I don't make noise.

741
00:42:41,684 --> 00:42:46,983
Rym: One thing I hated always was whenever my hard drives spun up on any case until modern ones, they'd rattle.

742
00:42:47,003 --> 00:42:47,766
Rym: They'd make noise.

743
00:42:48,188 --> 00:42:53,892
Rym: Now all good cases, anything that moves is mounted on rubber so you don't get that vibration noise coming out.

744
00:42:54,214 --> 00:42:54,414
Rym: Yep.

745
00:42:54,916 --> 00:42:55,157
Scott: Yeah.

746
00:42:55,218 --> 00:42:59,918
Scott: Generally, if you're building a computer, you want a case that makes building a computer, a pleasure.

747
00:42:59,938 --> 00:43:10,157
Scott: I mean, if you look at like a lot of old computers, you open those up, it basically sucked to build the computer with that case because it was hard to get drives in there.

748
00:43:10,177 --> 00:43:13,710
Scott: Uh, screws didn't fit holes weren't in the right places.

749
00:43:13,730 --> 00:43:16,689
Scott: It was very difficult to get the motherboard into the case.

750
00:43:18,071 --> 00:43:19,680
Scott: You couldn't get the power supply in or out.

751
00:43:19,701 --> 00:43:21,210
Scott: The power supply was part of the case.

752
00:43:21,771 --> 00:43:22,835
Scott: All sorts of terrible things.

753
00:43:23,176 --> 00:43:29,664
Scott: All the edges inside the case are very sharp and you'd cut yourself and you'd bleed and blood on the motherboard means a dead motherboard.

754
00:43:29,684 --> 00:43:30,086
Scott: Yep.

755
00:43:30,327 --> 00:43:30,869
Rym: Good God.

756
00:43:30,889 --> 00:43:32,254
Rym: I think we all learned that lesson.

757
00:43:32,314 --> 00:43:32,595
Rym: Yeah.

758
00:43:32,956 --> 00:43:41,522
Scott: So you want a case that has nice, sturdy, well measured parts that are easy to access, easy to get to, easy to work with.

759
00:43:41,843 --> 00:43:44,592
Scott: Lots of tool-less entry that just works.

760
00:43:44,913 --> 00:43:54,234
Scott: You don't want flimsy crap, but you know, you want something that's like, all right, this is going to let me install the motherboard by sliding out a tray, put the motherboard in the tray, all nice and easy.

761
00:43:54,535 --> 00:43:58,489
Scott: Slide the tray back in nice and easy to add cards to the computer.

762
00:43:58,530 --> 00:43:59,895
Scott: Just one screw in and out.

763
00:44:00,276 --> 00:44:00,578
Scott: Yep.

764
00:44:00,678 --> 00:44:02,465
Scott: Slide the drives in on little rails.

765
00:44:02,646 --> 00:44:03,650
Scott: Easy to take them in and out.

766
00:44:03,891 --> 00:44:10,056
Scott: Don't have to sit there like unscrewing a drive then pulling on it for like 10 minutes trying to get it out of there.

767
00:44:10,196 --> 00:44:19,470
Rym: In fact, in my current computer case, there is not one, but two dead hard drives that I would basically have to take the entire case apart to get out.

768
00:44:19,870 --> 00:44:21,095
Rym: So I just left them in there.

769
00:44:21,536 --> 00:44:21,878
Rym: Wow.

770
00:44:22,099 --> 00:44:22,400
Scott: Yeah.

771
00:44:22,861 --> 00:44:25,130
Rym: And I have two other hard drives stacked on top of them.

772
00:44:25,370 --> 00:44:25,732
Rym: Yep.

773
00:44:25,752 --> 00:44:27,380
Scott: Another thing I look for is quietness.

774
00:44:27,481 --> 00:44:34,512
Scott: As Rym said, the rubber grommets on the moving parts help a lot, but the most important thing when getting a quiet computer is the fans themselves.

775
00:44:34,652 --> 00:44:40,190
Rym: Very simply, you want large, slow fans, much more than you want small, fast fans.

776
00:44:40,410 --> 00:44:40,530
Scott: Yep.

777
00:44:40,611 --> 00:44:41,253
Scott: I mean, think about it.

778
00:44:41,334 --> 00:44:46,072
Scott: A small, fast fan makes a lot of noise, has high RPMs to push a lot of air.

779
00:44:46,533 --> 00:44:52,896
Scott: If you have a bigger fan, you can lower the RPM and lower the noise while still pushing the same quantity of air.

780
00:44:53,478 --> 00:44:55,365
Scott: So why would you ever use a smaller fan?

781
00:44:55,786 --> 00:45:02,592
Scott: Well, if you were stupid or your case was so small, it couldn't accommodate a small, a big fan, but that's a damn small case right there.

782
00:45:02,713 --> 00:45:05,384
Rym: Luckily, most modern cases take very large fans now.

783
00:45:05,445 --> 00:45:06,389
Rym: That seems to be the trend.

784
00:45:06,429 --> 00:45:08,117
Rym: Cases are getting better constantly.

785
00:45:08,438 --> 00:45:12,415
Scott: The cases I look at now, even the cheap ones, like you can go out and get a $20 case now.

786
00:45:12,435 --> 00:45:14,002
Scott: That's actually pretty cool.

787
00:45:14,142 --> 00:45:15,548
Rym: It's better than my current case.

788
00:45:15,769 --> 00:45:18,360
Rym: And my current case cost me $120 when I bought it.

789
00:45:18,501 --> 00:45:24,431
Scott: I still wouldn't buy the $20 cases now because they're probably made at a cheap plastic and they'll cut your arms up when you try to work with them.

790
00:45:24,551 --> 00:45:26,257
Rym: It's worth it to spend between $100 and $150 on a good case.

791
00:45:26,277 --> 00:45:33,626
Scott: If you're only going to build the computer once, I'd say it's only worth maybe $50 or $60.

792
00:45:33,626 --> 00:45:41,518
Scott: But if you're the kind of person who opens the case all the time to do all sorts of things, you definitely want to spend $100 or more to get a case that's easy to work with.

793
00:45:41,538 --> 00:45:45,796
Rym: I don't know, it's worth the $50 even if I'm building it once and I don't plan to do much in it.

794
00:45:46,138 --> 00:45:52,361
Rym: To have a case that feels solid, looks good, I can get access to if I ever need to, and that's a pleasure to build.

795
00:45:52,381 --> 00:46:01,841
Rym: I hate having to route cables around under things and my video card doesn't fit because the fan's in the way, and the hard drives don't fit because the case was manufactured and engineered poorly.

796
00:46:01,861 --> 00:46:10,759
Scott: Yeah, that can piss you off, but if it's only going to piss you off once in your life, and it'll be over with soon, then I think you don't have to spend so much more money.

797
00:46:10,779 --> 00:46:14,113
Rym: Well, there's also the problem that cheap cases tend to just break.

798
00:46:14,535 --> 00:46:15,217
Scott: That is true.

799
00:46:15,237 --> 00:46:21,076
Scott: I mean, look, the case I have had a little cheap plastic flap in front of the front USB ports.

800
00:46:21,217 --> 00:46:22,561
Scott: That plastic flap is gone.

801
00:46:23,324 --> 00:46:24,247
Scott: It's totally gone.

802
00:46:24,307 --> 00:46:25,150
Scott: It's never coming back.

803
00:46:26,091 --> 00:46:26,755
Scott: Forget about it.

804
00:46:27,157 --> 00:46:39,043
Scott: And how many other cases have I seen that are made of some cheap- they have some, like, fancy plastic bezel in the front, and over time it just cracks and chips away into a million pieces or shatters or whatever because it's some cheap piece of crap.

805
00:46:39,063 --> 00:46:44,626
Scott: or, you know, some metal on the inside gets bent and warps and now you can't get something out of there.

806
00:46:44,646 --> 00:46:46,955
Scott: It's, you know, cheap stuff is cheap stuff.

807
00:46:46,975 --> 00:46:47,818
Scott: You get what you pay for.

808
00:46:48,882 --> 00:46:56,316
Rym: Now, while it's very much related, and most people when they buy one, they buy the other at the same time, or you buy them in a set, but the power supply goes in the case.

809
00:46:56,738 --> 00:47:06,159
Rym: Not gonna really talk about the power supply because it's actually kind of complicated and difficult to give good advice when it comes to what kind of power supply- I don't even know what power supply to buy these days.

810
00:47:06,200 --> 00:47:10,239
Rym: You know how long it took me to figure out how many watts I needed for my new computer?

811
00:47:10,339 --> 00:47:11,062
Scott: Used to be easy.

812
00:47:11,142 --> 00:47:12,387
Scott: Now, not so easy anymore.

813
00:47:12,588 --> 00:47:13,572
Rym: Yeah, it used to be real easy.

814
00:47:13,672 --> 00:47:23,971
Rym: Every computer took generally the same wattage, but now with the SLI and the many, many, many hard drives and, well, if you're using an AMD, the processor, not so much of an issue with Intel anymore.

815
00:47:24,052 --> 00:47:32,557
Scott: Yeah, but it generally sucks to figure out what power supply you need, but generally, many cases will come with a power supply.

816
00:47:33,360 --> 00:47:38,458
Scott: Some don't, and then you have to go buy your own, so it's just a common pairing that you'll see.

817
00:47:38,478 --> 00:47:40,345
Rym: Yeah, and definitely factor it in.

818
00:47:40,425 --> 00:47:54,740
Scott: Yeah, when you're shopping for a case, make sure you check and see if the case comes with a power supply or not, because you might want it to, you might not want it to, but don't go buying a power supply you didn't want, and don't go buying an empty case and then not having a power supply.

819
00:47:54,840 --> 00:48:05,600
Rym: Yeah, especially if a power supply that would suit your needs plus some other case is 100 bucks, or the case you like is 100 bucks and you forget that now you got to drop another 100 bucks on a power supply.

820
00:48:05,620 --> 00:48:08,251
Scott: Yep, yep, just something to watch out for, people.

821
00:48:08,612 --> 00:48:17,611
Rym: Yep, however, power supplies, much like cases, you get what you pay for, you're generally better off spending a little bit more money to get something that you can probably trust a little bit more.

822
00:48:17,752 --> 00:48:20,362
Scott: Yeah, but you're also got to be wary of a lot of scam.

823
00:48:20,403 --> 00:48:25,646
Scott: power supplies where they say a whole bunch of marketing speak and the power supply is really not any better than the other one.

824
00:48:25,867 --> 00:48:29,538
Rym: A little hint, you don't need a 900 watt power supply yet.

825
00:48:29,558 --> 00:48:31,483
Scott: That's pretty much guaranteed.

826
00:48:32,165 --> 00:48:39,270
